/repos/KirstieJane/STEMMRoleModels/issue.body:
There are loads of ways to build websites, web apps and mobile apps. So which path should we choose?!

I've been working on a [responsive web design](https://www.coursera.org/learn/responsive-web-design/home/welcome) coursera course that recommends [Meteor](https://www.meteor.com/) as a platform. The benefits are that you build a website with meteor and then it creates the mobile apps for you so you don't have to do any work with the different native mobile platforms.

Another suggestion is [Foundation](http://foundation.zurb.com/) which is apparently nice and easy to use to create web apps.

A sensible plan may be to focus first on building a website rather than an app, and then transition to an app after that's developed.

What do you think?

/repos/KirstieJane/STEMMRoleModels/issue.body:
# Roadmap

Inspire future generations by providing the most exciting and diverse speakers for your conference.

## What are we aiming for?

The STEMM Role Models app (and associated website) allows you to access a searchable list of researchers who can speak about their work at your conference. It contains keywords and provides contact information, links to publications, blogs, social media profiles, links to youtube clips of previous presentations, and testimonials. Everyone in the database is identified as one or more of a selection of different under-represented groups in STEMM. The goal is to ensure that conference organisers are able to access a diverse and representative group of the most exciting researchers in their field around the world.

## What do we need to do?

* Build the database
    * Make a list of fields that can be included for each profile - see #11

* Apply for funding
    * Make a list of potential funders - see #12

* Create a "look" for the app - see #13

* Create the text for the app
    * Introduction
    * FAQs page
    * Instructions

## Short term goals

* Get on [collaborate](https://www.mozillascience.org/collaborate) - see #2
